{{refimprove|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Castell Bryn Gwyn |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = View across Castell Bryn Gwyn 11102009.JPG |alt = |caption = Castell Bryn Gwyn, view south from the bank |map = |map_caption = |map_type = |map_alt = |latitude = |longitude = |map_size = |location = Anglesey, Wales |region = Great Britain |coordinates = {{coord|53.1784|N|4.2978|W|region:GB|display=inline}} |type = enclosure |part_of = |length = |width = 64m |area = |height = 1.5m |builder = |material = clay, gravel, dry stone |built = end Neolithic |abandoned = |epochs = Neolithic, Iron Age, Roman |cultures = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = |condition = |ownership = |management = [[Cadw]] |public_access = Yes |website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> |notes = }}
'''Castell Bryn Gwyn''' is a [[prehistory|prehistoric]] site on the [[Isle of Anglesey]], west of [[Brynsiencyn]]. It is a circular clay and gravel bank covered with grass, still some 1.5m high and revetted externally by stone walls, which surround a level area some 54 metres in diameter. Its [[Welsh placenames|name]] means "White Hill Castle".{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}
The original use of this site is uncertain although it may have been a religious sanctuary. Later Neolithic pottery indicates use in this period, and it may have been a [[henge]] monument at this time. The earliest bank and ditch belong to the end of the neolithic period (2500-2000 BC).<ref>Cadw sign at the site</ref> During the Iron Age, the present wall was built, and it was refortified in Roman times and later.<ref name="Cyfeillion Ymddiriedolaeth Archaeolegol Gwynedd 2009. pp 32-33">Cyfeillion Ymddiriedolaeth Archaeolegol Gwynedd, Haf 2009. Friends of the Gwynedd Archaeological Trust, Summer 2009. Prehistoric Funerary and Ritual Survey, pp 32-33</ref>
Parking is exiguous; the site is accessible from the [[A4080]] by a footpath. Another path follows the low ridge, southwest over stiles to the [[Bryn Gwyn stones]], or northeast, past the site of the former stone circle of Tre'r Dryw Bach, some 800 metres to [[Caer Lêb]] where it meets a minor road with limited parking space.{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}
