'''Dr Glenn R. Foard''' (born c.1953) is an [[England|English]] landscape archaeologist, best known for discovering the location of the final phases of the [[Battle of Bosworth Field]] (1485).  He is Reader in Battlefield Archaeology at the [[University of Huddersfield]].<ref name="hud">[http://www.hud.ac.uk/ourstaff/profile/index.php?staffuid=entrgf Dr Glenn Foard - Profile - University of Huddersfield]. Accessed 30 June 2013</ref>

Foard obtained his first degree from [[University College, London]], in 1974, and went on to take an MA at the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology|Institute of Archaeology]].<ref name="hud" />  He later obtained a PhD in battlefield archaeology from the [[University of East Anglia]] (2008).

Foard is known for his work on major projects on behalf of the Battlefields Trust, [[English Heritage]], [[Historic Scotland]] and ''[[Time Team]]''.  While working for the Battlefields Trust, he led archaeological surveys of the sites of the [[Battle of Edgehill]] and the Battle of Bosworth.<ref>[http://www.battlefieldstrust.com/resource-centre/faq/periodpageview.asp?pageid=202&parentid=527 UK Battlefields Resource Centre]. Accessed 30 June 2013</ref>  Foard was appointed by [[Leicestershire County Council]] in 2005, in an exercise supported by the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]], to investigate the possible sites of the battle and try to establish its exact location.<ref>[http://www.bosworthbattlefield.com/battle/archaeology.htm Bosworth Battlefield Heritage Centre]. Accessed 12 January 2014</ref>

In 2009, Foard and his team discovered artefacts to support his theory that the site where the Bosworth Visitor Centre is currently located is several miles from the actual spot where the battle was fought.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2010/feb/19/battle-bosworth-site-found "Silver badge and lead shot pinpoint site of Battle of Bosworth", ''The Guardian'', 19 February 2010.] Accessed 30 June 2013</ref>  These included a silver-gilt badge in the shape of a [[White boar|boar]], the emblem of King [[Richard III of England]], who was killed in the battle.  [[Richard Holmes (military historian)|Richard Holmes]] called it "certainly the most important discovery about Bosworth in my lifetime".

