'''Indian Treasure Trove Act, 1878'''. (ACT NO. VI OF 1878. 1. ) (12 February 1878). An Act to amend the law relating to treasures found in [[India]].<ref>[http://asi.nic.in/pdf_data/9.pdf Indian Treasure Trove Act, 1878 ] Archaeological Survey of India 13 February 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.asichennai.gov.in/act_rules.html Antiquity - Acts & Rules]</ref>

It defines treasure specifically as "anything of any value hidden in the soil" and worth as little as 10 rupees (16 cents; 10 pence).
The finder of such treasure, according to this law, needs to inform the most senior local official of the "nature and amount or approximate value of such treasure and the place where it was found".<ref>[https://www.quora.com/What-is-the-law-in-India-for-someone-who-finds-buried-treasure-on-his-property What is the law in India for someone who finds buried treasure on his property?] Quora 13 February 2018</ref>{{better source|date=September 2018}} Also, if the finder fails to hand over the booty to the government, the "share of such treasure ... shall vest in Her Majesty", the Queen of [[England]].<ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-does-buried-treasure-in-india-still-belong-to-the-queen-india-to-wield-axe-on-287-laughable-colonial-british-laws-2024156 Does buried treasure in India still belong to the Queen? India to wield axe on 287 laughable colonial British laws] DNA India 7 October 2017</ref> It needs to be amended as its irrelevant now as the British left India in 1947 after India gained independence.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-29516976 Ten laws that India should scrap] BBC 7 October 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/11163623/Five-most-bizarre-British-Raj-laws-being-repealed-by-India.html Five most bizarre British Raj laws being repealed by India] The Telegraph 15 October 2014</ref>

== Law not user friendly for Tresure Hunters ==
The Law is not user friendly and encouraging to Hobby Metal detector enthusiasts or to professional Treasure hunters as practically all finds belong to the local Government however reforms in the law are being sought.<ref>[https://www.quora.com/Is-it-a-crime-in-india-to-not-inform-a-police-if-someone-found-treasure-coffers-at-some-unclaimed-place-or-even-in-his-own-place-If-yes-then-how-heavily-can-it-be-punished-in-a-court-of-India Is it a crime in india to not inform a police if someone found treasure/coffers at some unclaimed place or even in his own place?] Quora 13 February 2018</ref><ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Archaeological-plundering-in-India-getting-worrisome-say-experts/articleshow/20358213.cms?from=mdr Archaeological plundering in India getting worrisome, say experts] Times of India 31 May 2013</ref>

All major metal detecting, excavations and treasure hunts per se are carried out by India's nodal agency setup for the purpose, the [[Archaeological Survey of India]].

